**Q2: `r, p, q` combinations** TC and SC `O(R*P*Q*4)`

We need to draw all the chars of `r` from `p` and `q` in order. Suppose we need to get `r[i]` next and our next char has to be `p[j]` or later and `q[k]` or later. We also probably need to know if we've taken from `p` or `q` yet. So current state is `int i, int j, int k, bool tp, bool tq`.

To take char `i` we can either
* find a copy of `r[i]` in `p[j] ... p[p.size()-1]`, then continue with `i+1, j'+1, k, true, tq` where j' is the index we matched
* find a copy of `r[i]` in `q[k] .. q[q.size()-1]`, then continue with `i+1, j, k'+1, tp, tq` where k' is the index we matched

To avoid duplicate work we can cache the results for these `O(100^3 * 4)` combinations which will fit in the GB of memory limit.

```C++
long long countWays(const string &r, const string &p, const string &q) {
  const int R=r.size(), P=p.size(), Q=q.size();
  constexpr long long M = 1'000'000'007;

  unordered_map<tuple<int, int, int, bool, bool>, int> cache;
  auto ways = [&](int i, int j, int k, bool tp, bool tq, auto&& ways) -> long long {
    {
      auto it = cache.find({i, j, k, tp, tq});
      if (it != cache.end()) return it->second;
    }

    if (i==R || j == P && !tp || k == Q && !tq) {
      cache.emplace({i, j, k, tp, tq}, 0);
      return 0;
    }

    long long ans = 0;
    for (int jj=j; jj < P; ++jj) if (r[i] == p[jj]) ans = (ans + ways(i+1, jj+1, k, true, tq, ways))%M;
    for (int kk=k; kk<Q; ++kk) if (r[i] == q[kk]) ans = (ans + ways(i+1, j, kk+1, tp, true, ways))%M;
    cache.emplace({i, j, k, tp, tq}, ans);
    return ans;
  };

  return ways(0, 0, 0, false, false, ways);
```

Note that this code looks pretty simple but it definitely took me a while to figure out how to avoid over-counting things. Doesn't help that my C++ is rusty, I usually do Python (`@cache` decorator is the goat).
